# Architecture Alignment

REMI is an agent operating system — a runtime that lets an AI agent
monitor a director's book of business, detect situations, and act
autonomously. Four top-level packages: `agent/` (OS kernel — all AI
infrastructure), `domain/` (real estate product), `types/` (shared
vocabulary), `shell/` (composition root). The directory tree is the
documentation.

## Package Placement

### The Agent (`agent/` — all AI infrastructure)

| Subpackage | What it is | Depends on |
|---|-----|---|
| `agent/llm/` | LLM provider ports + adapters | `types/` |
| `agent/vectors/` | Embedding ports + adapters | `types/` |
| `agent/sandbox/` | Code execution ports + adapters | `types/` |
| `agent/observe/` | Logging, tracing | `types/` |
| `agent/signals/` | Signal framework — types, stores, producers | `types/`, `agent/graph/` |
| `agent/ingestion/` | Generic LLM pipeline runner | `agent/llm/` |
| `agent/graph/` | Knowledge graph — types, bridge, retriever | `agent/vectors/`, `types/` |
| `agent/documents/` | Document types, stores, parsers | `agent/db/` |
| `agent/db/` | Database engine + tables | `types/` |
| `agent/runtime/` | LLM execution loop, tool dispatch, streaming | `agent/llm/`, `agent/observe/` |
| `agent/context/` | Perception, context building, intent | `agent/signals/`, `agent/graph/`, `agent/vectors/` |
| `agent/conversation/` | Thread management, compression | `agent/llm/` |
| `agent/tools/` | Domain-agnostic tool implementations | `agent/sandbox/`, `agent/vectors/`, `agent/observe/` |

### The Domain (`domain/` — real estate product)

| Subpackage | What it is | Depends on |
|---|-----|---|
| `domain/portfolio/` | Entity DTOs, protocols, rules | `types/` |
| `domain/stores/` | RE persistence adapters | `domain/portfolio/`, `agent/db/` |
| `domain/queries/` | RE query services | `domain/portfolio/`, `domain/stores/` |
| `domain/evaluators/` | RE signal producers (delinquency, lease, etc.) | `domain/portfolio/`, `domain/stores/`, `agent/signals/` |
| `domain/ingestion/` | RE inbound data pipeline | `domain/portfolio/`, `domain/stores/`, `agent/documents/`, `agent/ingestion/` |
| `domain/ontology/` | RE knowledge graph schema | `agent/graph/` |
| `domain/search/` | RE-aware hybrid search | `agent/graph/`, `agent/vectors/` |
| `domain/tools/` | RE agent capabilities | `domain/queries/`, `domain/evaluators/`, `domain/ingestion/`, `domain/ontology/`, `domain/search/` |
| `domain/agents/` | RE agent YAML manifests | `agent/` |

### Shared Vocabulary

| Package | What it is | Depends on |
|---|-----|---|
| `types/` | Pure vocabulary — ids, clock, errors, enums | nothing |

### Composition Root

| Package | What it is | Depends on |
|---|-----|---|
| `shell/` | DI container, settings, API mountpoint, CLI | everything |

## New Modules — Placement Checklist

Before creating a file or adding significant logic, answer:

1. **Which of the four?**
   - AI infrastructure (LLM, embeddings, sandbox, tracing, signals,
     graph, documents, execution) -> `agent/`
   - Property management business logic -> `domain/`
   - Pure primitives, no I/O -> `types/`
   - HTTP routes, CLI, DI wiring -> `shell/`

2. **Which subpackage?** (see tables above)

3. **Dependency direction:** `domain/` imports from `agent/` — never
   the reverse. `shell/` imports from both. `types/` imports nothing.

4. **Hexagonal rule:** Concrete infrastructure libraries (`psycopg2`,
   `openai`, `anthropic`, `docker`) live in adapter files within the
   owning subpackage. Only `shell/config/container.py` wires them.

5. **Discoverability:** Could an LLM discover this capability via
   the directory tree, `--help`, or tool registry?

## Interface Segregation

Repository ports live in `domain/portfolio/protocols.py` as **narrow,
per-entity protocols** (e.g. `LeaseRepository`, `UnitRepository`).

- **New code** must depend on the **narrowest** protocol.
- When touching existing code that takes a composite store, narrow
  the type if the function only uses one or two protocols.

## Container Discipline

`shell/config/container.py` must stay a **thin wiring layer**.

- Attributes only consumed internally -> local variables, not `self.*`.
- Factory functions belong in the module that owns the thing being built.
- Before adding a new `self.*` attribute, verify it will be read externally.

## Import Rules

- **Never use `typing.TYPE_CHECKING`.** If you need it, the dependency
  graph is wrong.
- All imports must be direct and honest.
- No circular import workarounds.
- `domain/` imports from `agent/` — never the reverse.

## Error Propagation Rules

- **No silent exception swallowing.** Every `except` block must either
  re-raise or log at `warning`+ with `exc_info=True`.
- `except Exception: pass` and `except Exception: continue` are banned.
- Catch-and-continue must record failures in a result object.
- Narrow the exception type when the failure mode is known.

## Type Strictness

- **No `dict[str, Any]`** as a return type or parameter.
- **No `-> Any`** return annotations.
- **No `list[dict]`** — model the list items.
- When touching existing `Any`/`dict` code, narrow the annotation.

## File Size Gates

- **Port files** (ABCs / Protocols): flag at **8 abstract methods**.
- **Implementation files**: flag at **300 lines**.
- **Container**: flag at **250 lines**.

## Boundary Model Conventions

Types flow **inward** — outer packages import from inner packages.

| Location | Owns | Examples |
|----|---|----|
| `domain/portfolio/models.py` | Entity DTOs | `Property`, `Unit`, `Lease` |
| `domain/queries/*.py` | Service read-models | `RentRollResult`, `PortfolioOverview` |
| `shell/api/*/schemas.py` | Re-exports + HTTP-only types | Request bodies, envelope wrappers |
| CLI commands | nothing — format what services return | `model_dump()` -> render |

### Write operations

Mutating repository methods return `WriteResult[T]` with a `WriteOutcome`
discriminator (`CREATED`, `UPDATED`, `NOOP`).

## Dead Code Policy

- Do not leave CLI commands unreachable from the entry point.
- Do not leave tool registration functions that are never called.
- Backward-compat aliases get a `# COMPAT:` comment and a removal condition.

## Naming Conventions

- Files that define a class plus its factory: name after the concept.
- Factory functions: `build_<thing>()` — lives in the owning module.
- Seeding / initialization: `seed_<thing>()`.
